<subSubSection pageId="111" pageNumber="112" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="111.[151,1436,1037,1278]" pageId="111" pageNumber="112">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,273,1073,1098]" pageId="111" pageNumber="112">Notes.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cresson" authorityYear="1878" box="[281,491,1073,1098]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="111" pageNumber="112" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mucida">
<emphasis box="[281,491,1073,1098]" italics="true" pageId="111" pageNumber="112">Megachile mucida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is poorly represented in historical collections, especially from the northern portion of its range, but it is now quite common in late spring in the Lansing area of Michigan. Its adult emergence was among the earliest of 
<taxonomicName box="[418,536,1145,1170]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="111" pageNumber="112" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[418,536,1145,1170]" italics="true" pageId="111" pageNumber="112">Megachile</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species in the area and its coloration is distinctive, except with respect to separation from its close relatives 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cresson" authorityYear="1878" box="[532,652,1181,1206]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="111" pageNumber="112" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gemula">
<emphasis box="[532,555,1182,1205]" italics="true" pageId="111" pageNumber="112">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[569,652,1181,1206]" italics="true" pageId="111" pageNumber="112">gemula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Pengelly" baseAuthorityYear="1955" box="[706,894,1181,1206]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="111" pageNumber="112" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="melanophaea">
<emphasis box="[706,729,1182,1205]" italics="true" pageId="111" pageNumber="112">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[743,894,1181,1206]" italics="true" pageId="111" pageNumber="112">melanophaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. From those, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cresson" authorityYear="1878" box="[1047,1167,1181,1206]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="111" pageNumber="112" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mucida">
<emphasis box="[1047,1070,1182,1205]" italics="true" pageId="111" pageNumber="112">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1084,1167,1181,1206]" italics="true" pageId="111" pageNumber="112">mucida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished by characters of the female mandible and of the male tarsi (
<bibRefCitation author="Mitchell" box="[779,940,1217,1242]" firstAuthor="Mitchell" pageId="111" pageNumber="112" pagination="1 - 557" refId="ref96606" refString="Mitchell, T. B. (1962) Bees of the Eastern United States: volume II. N. C. Agricultural Experimental Station Technical Bulletin, 152, 1 - 557." type="book chapter" year="1962">Mitchell 1962</bibRefCitation>
) and subtle differences in the distribution of pale hairs. 
<bibRefCitation author="Gibbs" box="[273,422,1253,1278]" firstAuthor="Gibbs" pageId="111" pageNumber="112" pagination="17 - 24" refId="ref88558" refString="Gibbs, J. (2017) Notes on the nests of Augochloropsis metallica fulgida and Megachile mucida in central Michigan (Hymenoptera: Halictidae, Megachilidae). The Great Lakes Entomologist, 50, 17 - 24." type="journal article" year="2017">Gibbs (2017)</bibRefCitation>
provided details on its distribution in Michigan and described its nesting habits.
</paragraph>
